nd value the centrality of care in their lives, homes, and classrooms. Luttrell’s immersive, creative, and layered analysis of the young people’s images and narratives boldly refutes biased assumptions about working-class childhoods and re-envisions schools as inclusive, imaginative, and care-ful spaces. With an accompanying website featuring additional digital resources (childrenframingchildhoods.com), this book challenges us to see differently and, thus, set our sights on a better future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildrenxSocial conditionszMassachusettszWorcester. 0aWorking class familiesxSocial conditionszMassachusettszWorcester. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831111967180 cprintz978144735330040uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447353324?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447353324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447353324/original  a978-3-11-119671-8  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles